  "prompt": "Can cataracts affect younger people? What are the most common causes of it?",
  "response": "Yes, cataracts can affect younger people, although they are more commonly associated with aging. In younger individuals, several factors can lead to the development of cataracts. The most common causes include:\n\n1. **Genetic Factors:** Some people may be genetically predisposed to developing cataracts at an earlier age. Congenital cataracts, for instance, can be present at birth or develop during childhood.\n\n2. **Trauma:** Eye injuries, whether from accidents, sports, or other physical impacts, can lead to the formation of cataracts.\n\n3. **Medical Conditions:** Certain medical conditions like diabetes, galactosemia, and other metabolic disorders can increase the risk of cataracts in younger individuals.\n\n4. **Medications:** Long-term use of certain medications, such as corticosteroids, can contribute to the development of cataracts.\n\n5. **Radiation Exposure:** Exposure to radiation, including from treatments for other medical conditions or excessive UV light without eye protection, has been linked to cataract formation.\n\n6. **Infections:** Some infections during pregnancy, such as rubella, can lead to congenital cataracts in newborns.\n\n7. **Lifestyle Factors:** Smoking, excessive alcohol consumption, and poor diet lacking in essential nutrients can also contribute to the development of cataracts at a younger age.\n\nRegular eye examinations can help in early detection and management of cataracts, regardless of age. If you or someone you know is experiencing symptoms such as blurry vision, difficulty seeing at night, or seeing halos around lights, it's important to consult an eye care professional.",
